Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.836 --> 00:00:06.005
JOHN OLIVER: North Korea...
America's number one excuse

00:00:06.105 --> 00:00:07.506
for putting off chores
this week.

00:00:07.706 --> 00:00:09.776
"Y'know, I could do laundry,
but if the world's

00:00:09.876 --> 00:00:13.012
about to erupt into nuclear war,
what really is the point?"

00:00:13.112 --> 00:00:14.046
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:00:14.446 --> 00:00:16.949
North Korea has clearly been
on everyone's minds this week,

00:00:17.049 --> 00:00:18.317
and I think you know why.

00:00:18.417 --> 00:00:21.287 line:0%
President Trump and North Korea
escalate the war of words,

00:00:21.388 --> 00:00:24.590 line:0%
lobbing new threats
and sending new tweets.

00:00:24.690 --> 00:00:27.359 line:0%
North Korea now accusing the
president of the United States

00:00:27.459 --> 00:00:31.864 line:0%
of pushing the world to, quote,
"the brink of nuclear war."

00:00:32.631 --> 00:00:36.402
Wow. When Twitter was
invented, I bet even they

00:00:36.502 --> 00:00:39.138
didn't imagine that it would
one day lead us to the brink

00:00:39.239 --> 00:00:40.907
-of nuclear Armageddon.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:00:41.007 --> 00:00:43.075
It's like if the invention
of the Furby had led

00:00:43.175 --> 00:00:45.111
-to the Sudanese civil war.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:00:45.211 --> 00:00:47.146
Who knew that that's
where it was headed?

00:00:47.246 --> 00:00:48.247
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:00:48.347 --> 00:00:50.483
Now, tensions have sharply
escalated this week,

00:00:50.583 --> 00:00:52.418
which is a little surprising,
given that the world

00:00:52.518 --> 00:00:53.953
has been dealing
with North Korea's

00:00:54.053 --> 00:00:56.022
provocative missile tests
for years now.

00:00:56.122 --> 00:00:58.024
Just two weeks ago,
they were doing this.

00:00:58.491 --> 00:01:00.225 line:0%
CORRESPONDENT:<i> North Korea fires
 yet another missile,</i>

00:01:00.326 --> 00:01:02.595 line:0%
<i> but Pyongyang claims this one</i>

00:01:02.695 --> 00:01:04.196 line:0%
<i> will be able to hit the
 U.S. mainland,</i>

00:01:04.297 --> 00:01:06.799 line:0%
<i> striking cities like
 Los Angeles, Denver,</i>

00:01:07.066 --> 00:01:10.202 line:0%
<i> Chicago, and possibly even
 New York and Boston.</i>

00:01:10.569 --> 00:01:13.772
Wait! New York?
I live in New York!

00:01:13.873 --> 00:01:16.176
-This shit just got real!
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:01:16.276 --> 00:01:18.978
No, I think if anyone is--
if everyone is really honest,

00:01:19.078 --> 00:01:21.514
your level of fear
over the North Korea situation

00:01:21.614 --> 00:01:23.449
is in direct proportion
to whether or not

00:01:23.550 --> 00:01:25.451
they can hit the exact place
where you live.

00:01:25.551 --> 00:01:26.285
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:01:26.385 --> 00:01:28.487
We film this show
on 57th street.

00:01:28.587 --> 00:01:31.791
If you told me that the blast
radius stops at 56th street,

00:01:31.891 --> 00:01:33.960
I'd think, "Well, I hope nothing
happens,

00:01:34.060 --> 00:01:36.662
but we've still got time
before things get serious."

00:01:36.762 --> 00:01:37.730
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:01:38.298 --> 00:01:41.334
-Now, it is-- it is worth
properly understanding
-(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS)

00:01:41.868 --> 00:01:43.970
what North Korea is
currently capable of,

00:01:44.070 --> 00:01:46.205
because while their missiles
may be able to reach us

00:01:46.305 --> 00:01:48.407
and they do have
nuclear warheads,

00:01:48.841 --> 00:01:51.678
most experts believe that they
don't yet have the technology

00:01:51.778 --> 00:01:53.947
to reliably hit
the U.S. mainland,

00:01:54.047 --> 00:01:57.417
so that is reassuring.
Although, on the other hand

00:01:57.617 --> 00:02:00.186
a recent Pentagon assessment did
suggest that they could cross

00:02:00.286 --> 00:02:01.821
that threshold next year.

00:02:01.921 --> 00:02:05.291
So, if a job interviewer asks
you, "Where do you see yourself

00:02:05.391 --> 00:02:06.492
in five years' time?"

00:02:06.592 --> 00:02:09.629
It is now perfectly acceptable
just to scream in terror

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:11.831
-into their face.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:02:11.931 --> 00:02:15.335
Look, this is clearly a very
serious situation,

00:02:15.435 --> 00:02:16.802
requiring a deft hand.

00:02:16.902 --> 00:02:19.605
And, sadly,
that's not what it got.

00:02:20.306 --> 00:02:24.210
North Korea best not
make any more threats

00:02:24.310 --> 00:02:25.612
to the United states.

00:02:26.713 --> 00:02:30.517
They will be met
with fire and fury,

00:02:31.317 --> 00:02:33.719
like the world has never seen.

00:02:34.186 --> 00:02:38.424
"Fire and fury." The only way
that that is not terrifying

00:02:38.524 --> 00:02:41.427
is if you report it the way one
newspaper actually did in Maine

00:02:41.527 --> 00:02:44.364
saying, "Trump warns
of fire and furry."

00:02:44.464 --> 00:02:45.431
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

00:02:45.532 --> 00:02:48.001
In which case, Trump was
threatening to send this

00:02:48.101 --> 00:02:51.404
to North Korea, which is a very
different kind of threat.

00:02:52.171 --> 00:02:54.907
Now-- now, in response,
North Korea announced plans

00:02:55.007 --> 00:02:58.611
to fire missiles that would land
just off the coast of the U.S.
territory of Guam,

00:02:58.711 --> 00:03:02.381
which is frightening,
although not unprecedented.

00:03:02.615 --> 00:03:04.650
They have made similar
threats before.

00:03:04.750 --> 00:03:07.887
But what is different this time,
obviously, is that we now have

00:03:07.987 --> 00:03:11.023
a president who has the general
temperament of a wet cat.

00:03:11.323 --> 00:03:13.726
And, in response
to that Guam threat,

00:03:13.826 --> 00:03:15.561
Trump promptly doubled down.

00:03:15.794 --> 00:03:17.964 line:0%
Frankly, uh, the people
that were questioning

00:03:18.064 --> 00:03:19.999 line:0%
that statement,
"Was it too tough?"

00:03:20.099 --> 00:03:21.668 line:0%
Maybe it wasn't tough enough.

00:03:21.768 --> 00:03:24.904 line:0%
If anything, that statement
may not be tough enough.

00:03:26.972 --> 00:03:28.407 line:0%
Well, you'll see, you'll see.

00:03:29.008 --> 00:03:31.911
"Yeah, we're gonna go
with that bomb more destructive

00:03:32.011 --> 00:03:34.113
than the nuclear bomb.
Why? I don't know!

00:03:34.213 --> 00:03:36.482
Who cares that it doesn't exist?
Sincerely yours, Donald Trump.

00:03:36.582 --> 00:03:38.617
I'm not writing a letter.
I'm talking. Says you!

00:03:38.717 --> 00:03:39.719
Fake news. Goodbye!"

00:03:39.819 --> 00:03:41.287
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS, APPLAUDS)

00:03:41.387 --> 00:03:44.489
So, tonight,
we thought we would ask,

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:46.792
"What, exactly,
is North Korea thinking?

00:03:47.193 --> 00:03:48.794
How did we get into this mess?

00:03:48.894 --> 00:03:50.596
And what can we possibly
do about it?"

00:03:50.696 --> 00:03:53.299
And let's start by trying
to understand just a little bit

00:03:53.399 --> 00:03:54.733
more about North Korea.

00:03:54.833 --> 00:03:57.937
And that in itself is difficult.
It's one of the most isolated

00:03:58.037 --> 00:03:59.272
and insular nations on earth.

00:03:59.372 --> 00:04:01.640
If you know anything about it
at all, it's probably just that

00:04:01.741 --> 00:04:05.110
they have a wacky totalitarian
leader who loves

00:04:05.210 --> 00:04:07.480
military parades
and Dennis Rodman,

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:10.416
and who really didn't like that
Seth Rogen movie

00:04:10.616 --> 00:04:11.584
about his assassination.

00:04:11.684 --> 00:04:13.319
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)
-And it can be hard

00:04:13.419 --> 00:04:15.521
to trust any information
about North Korea,

00:04:15.621 --> 00:04:18.724
because lots of it is
inaccurate for multiple reasons.

00:04:18.825 --> 00:04:20.993
First, there's the outright
state propaganda,

00:04:21.093 --> 00:04:24.296
which glorifies North Korea's
leaders, the Kim family.

00:04:24.563 --> 00:04:27.600
Just last year, we showed you
western journalists being taken

00:04:27.700 --> 00:04:29.568
on a tour
of a historic target range,

00:04:29.668 --> 00:04:32.004
where they learned something
suspiciously impressive

00:04:32.104 --> 00:04:33.639
about Kim Jong-Un's father.

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:37.042 line:0%
Comrade Kim Jong-il shot three
bullets and three of them

00:04:37.142 --> 00:04:38.143 line:0%
got bulls-eye.

00:04:38.244 --> 00:04:39.412 line:0%
-They all got bulls-eye?
-Mm-hmm.

00:04:39.512 --> 00:04:42.548 line:0%
-And how old was he at the time?
-He was 7-year-old.

00:04:42.648 --> 00:04:43.482 line:0%
A 7-year-old's got

00:04:43.582 --> 00:04:44.850 line:0%
-three bulls-eyes?
-Mm-hmm. yeah.

00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:47.753 line:0%
-That's pretty impressive.
-(LAUGHS) Mm-hmm.

00:04:48.154 --> 00:04:49.922
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:04:50.022 --> 00:04:52.725
I mean, that-- that is
the "mm-hmm"

00:04:52.958 --> 00:04:55.828
of someone who really wants
to shut down a conversation.

00:04:56.462 --> 00:04:58.264
She sounds like a parent
fielding questions

00:04:58.364 --> 00:04:59.698
about where babies come from.

00:04:59.798 --> 00:05:02.368
-"So, a stork brings the baby?"
-"Mm-hmm."

00:05:02.701 --> 00:05:05.437
"It carries an eight-pound baby
through the air in its mouth?"

00:05:05.537 --> 00:05:06.538
"Mm-hmm."

00:05:06.638 --> 00:05:08.407
-"Isn't that dangerous?"
-"Mm-hmm."

00:05:08.507 --> 00:05:10.643
"Where does the stork get
the babies?"

00:05:10.743 --> 00:05:14.846
"Storks fuck! They fuck each
other! Storks fuck each other,

00:05:14.947 --> 00:05:17.249
and the baby comes
out of the stork's vagina!

00:05:17.449 --> 00:05:20.219
Don't ask for the truth
if you can't handle it!"

00:05:20.319 --> 00:05:21.821
(AUDIENCE CHEERS AND APPLAUDS)

00:05:22.588 --> 00:05:24.023
But, here's the thing.

00:05:25.291 --> 00:05:28.093
Inaccuracies like that are
easy to spot.

00:05:28.193 --> 00:05:30.129
What is trickier is that a lot
of eye-catching western

00:05:30.229 --> 00:05:32.498
reporting about North Korea
can be shakily sourced,

00:05:32.598 --> 00:05:33.599
like this one.

00:05:34.233 --> 00:05:37.102
JOY-ANN REID:<i> The BBC reports
 all of the men in the
 hermit kingdom</i>

00:05:37.202 --> 00:05:40.873
<i>must now sport the same haircut
as the dear leader, Kim Jong-un.</i>

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:43.743
<i> His look was known as
 the Chinese smuggler haircut</i>

00:05:43.843 --> 00:05:46.645
<i>not too long ago in the region,
 but now it will be known as</i>

00:05:46.745 --> 00:05:49.548
"The haircut every man
in North Korea must have."

00:05:49.815 --> 00:05:50.916
Lucky them.

00:05:51.016 --> 00:05:52.284
Here's the thing...

00:05:52.685 --> 00:05:55.321
There is no solid evidence
that that story is true.

00:05:55.421 --> 00:05:58.190
But it is seductive because it
sounds like it could be.

00:05:58.391 --> 00:05:59.625
It's like if you saw
the headline

00:05:59.725 --> 00:06:01.794
"Trump to NATO:
I invented Squirrels."

00:06:02.094 --> 00:06:04.663
You'd believe it because it
sounds like something

00:06:04.763 --> 00:06:08.267
he would've claimed, even though
as of this taping, he has not.

00:06:08.968 --> 00:06:11.970
And, while it may not be true
that all men had to get

00:06:12.070 --> 00:06:14.974
the same haircut as Kim Jong-un,
state TV did run a series

00:06:15.074 --> 00:06:17.476
called "Let Us Trim
Our Hair in Accordance

00:06:17.576 --> 00:06:18.877
with the Socialist Lifestyle."

00:06:19.244 --> 00:06:23.182
And it's weird when a verifiable
truth is almost as strange

00:06:23.282 --> 00:06:24.283
as a wild rumor.

00:06:24.683 --> 00:06:27.953
It's like how the "Richard Gere
Put a Gerbil in His Ass" story

00:06:28.053 --> 00:06:30.523
is completely false,
but what if the truth

00:06:30.623 --> 00:06:33.092
was that he engaged in
consensual mutual anal play

00:06:33.192 --> 00:06:36.295
with a chinchilla?
That would still be bizarre.

00:06:36.495 --> 00:06:38.497
You wouldn't have
to exaggerate that.

00:06:39.164 --> 00:06:41.734
And sometimes, the truth
about life in North Korea

00:06:41.834 --> 00:06:44.303
can be just as striking
as the urban legends.

00:06:44.403 --> 00:06:47.507
For instance, you may have seen
claims online that every teacher

00:06:47.607 --> 00:06:50.475
in North Korea is obligated
to play the accordion.

00:06:50.976 --> 00:06:52.177
We could not confirm that.

00:06:52.277 --> 00:06:55.447
Although, in trying to, we did
discover that North Korea

00:06:55.547 --> 00:06:58.884
does love the accordion
to a surprising extent.

00:06:58.984 --> 00:07:02.488
The country is full of them.
Here is an accordion factory.

00:07:02.588 --> 00:07:04.890
Here's some schoolchildren
playing the accordion.

00:07:04.990 --> 00:07:07.159
Here's Kim Jong-un
looking at an accordion.

00:07:07.659 --> 00:07:10.162
Here is an air combat exercise
where the camera pans

00:07:10.263 --> 00:07:11.797
<i> across pilots, and guess what?</i>

00:07:12.331 --> 00:07:15.301
<i>-Yep. It's a fucking accordion.</i>
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

00:07:15.535 --> 00:07:17.569
They also have a very
popular song called

00:07:17.669 --> 00:07:20.306
"Nothing to Envy in the World"
that begins with the line

00:07:20.406 --> 00:07:22.608
"The sky is blue,
my heart is merry,

00:07:22.708 --> 00:07:24.810
let the sound
of accordions ring."

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:27.947
And then there is this video
of North Koreans playing

00:07:28.047 --> 00:07:30.116
the last song that
you would expect.

00:07:30.616 --> 00:07:33.553
♪ (ACCORDIONS PLAYING
"TAKE ON ME" BY A-HA ) ♪

00:07:42.361 --> 00:07:43.930
-Yes.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:07:44.197 --> 00:07:46.231
That is North Korean
accordionists playing

00:07:46.331 --> 00:07:47.400
"Take on Me."

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:50.736
So beat that, everyone else
who plays the accordion!

00:07:51.404 --> 00:07:53.739
By which I mean exactly
two old French men

00:07:53.839 --> 00:07:55.374
and one "Weird Al" Yankovic.

00:07:56.041 --> 00:07:59.578
And if you think that that is
the most amazing piece

00:07:59.678 --> 00:08:01.647
of North Korean Pop culture
that you're gonna see tonight,

00:08:01.747 --> 00:08:02.748
you are wrong.

00:08:02.848 --> 00:08:05.350
Because let me introduce
you to<i> Pulgasari,</i>

00:08:05.651 --> 00:08:08.987
a 1985 movie known as the
"North Korean<i> Godzilla."</i>

00:08:09.087 --> 00:08:10.589
The whole thing is incredible,

00:08:10.689 --> 00:08:12.958
but this is undoubtedly
my favorite part.

00:08:13.425 --> 00:08:16.028
(DEVILISHLY LAUGHING)

00:08:17.930 --> 00:08:19.765
(GROWLING)

00:08:19.865 --> 00:08:21.367
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:08:26.205 --> 00:08:28.607
You know why I love that?
It's relatable.

00:08:28.807 --> 00:08:32.678
No matter where you're
from or what your religious
or political beliefs are,

00:08:32.778 --> 00:08:35.281
at some point, everybody
has been about to decapitate

00:08:35.381 --> 00:08:38.383
someone and then out of nowhere
a baby monster jumps up

00:08:38.483 --> 00:08:39.785
and takes a bite
out of your sword.

00:08:39.885 --> 00:08:42.555
-It works because it resonates.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:08:42.822 --> 00:08:44.689
And look, look,
we're all having fun.

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:46.525
We're laughing
about North Korea!

00:08:46.625 --> 00:08:50.396
And it can be very funny,
but the very fact

00:08:50.496 --> 00:08:51.631
that that is true

00:08:51.731 --> 00:08:54.466
can be extremely frustrating
to journalists who cover it.

00:08:55.300 --> 00:08:57.035
BARBARA DEMICK:<i> It's always,
 you know, an exaggeration,</i>

00:08:57.135 --> 00:08:59.838
<i> and a parody, and you know,
 kind of a freak show.</i>

00:09:00.139 --> 00:09:03.041 line:0%
Which, I think, those of us who
cover North Korea

00:09:03.642 --> 00:09:06.612 line:0%
find a little bit distressing,
because it's not actually

00:09:06.712 --> 00:09:10.950 line:0%
very funny to the 24 million
people who live there.

00:09:11.817 --> 00:09:13.886
She's right.
She's absolutely right.

00:09:13.986 --> 00:09:16.822
And even when North Korea is
objectively funny,

00:09:16.922 --> 00:09:19.825
like with<i> Pulgasari,</i>
it has dark undertones.

00:09:19.925 --> 00:09:23.162
Because Kim Jong-il got that
movie made by abducting

00:09:23.262 --> 00:09:25.397
two of south Korea's biggest
names in film,

00:09:25.497 --> 00:09:27.833
and forcing them to make movies
for him, for years.

00:09:27.933 --> 00:09:30.102
And you know what?
They did eventually escape,

00:09:30.202 --> 00:09:32.237
so I'm gonna go ahead
and say, and I know

00:09:32.337 --> 00:09:33.706
this is not gonna be a
popular opinion,

00:09:33.806 --> 00:09:35.808
but, if that's what it took

00:09:35.908 --> 00:09:37.676
to give us that baby
monster scene,

00:09:37.776 --> 00:09:39.010
it was fucking worth it.

00:09:39.277 --> 00:09:40.445
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)
-Just my opinion!

00:09:40.545 --> 00:09:41.780
Just my opinion.

00:09:42.314 --> 00:09:44.717
But the underlying truth
of North Korea is that

00:09:44.817 --> 00:09:48.754
it is a dark place, not just
figuratively, but literally.

00:09:48.854 --> 00:09:51.390
You can get a sense of how
little development there--

00:09:51.490 --> 00:09:54.126
has been there when you
look at it from space.

00:09:54.493 --> 00:09:57.295
See that void where there
is almost no lights?

00:09:57.796 --> 00:09:58.797
That's North Korea.

00:09:59.297 --> 00:10:01.601
It looks like a divorced dad's
Christmas tree,

00:10:01.701 --> 00:10:03.569
where he gave up halfway through
hanging the lights,

00:10:03.669 --> 00:10:06.371
got drunk and fell asleep
watching Ken Burns'<i> Baseball.</i>

00:10:07.506 --> 00:10:10.609
And the Kim family is known
for their bone-chilling cruelty

00:10:10.709 --> 00:10:11.710
and mismanagement.

00:10:12.177 --> 00:10:14.313
They were largely
responsible for the deaths
of somewhere between

00:10:14.513 --> 00:10:19.151
600,000 and 2.5 million people
during a famine in the 1990s.

00:10:19.251 --> 00:10:22.320
And we know that there are
large, brutal camps

00:10:22.554 --> 00:10:25.157
where political dissidents
are imprisoned, sometimes

00:10:25.257 --> 00:10:26.959
alongside their
extended families.

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:29.829
REPORTER:<i> Satellite images
 show their scale,</i>

00:10:29.929 --> 00:10:32.264
<i> but for a picture of what
 they're really like,</i>

00:10:32.698 --> 00:10:34.900
<i> we can only rely on those
 who've been there.</i>

00:10:35.634 --> 00:10:38.170 line:0%
(MAN SPEAKING KOREAN)

00:10:51.683 --> 00:10:53.819
REPORTER:<i> These sketches are
 the recollections of other</i>

00:10:53.919 --> 00:10:55.954
<i> prisoners who've managed
 to escape the camps.</i>

00:10:56.689 --> 00:10:59.358
That is truly horrific.
But the existence,

00:10:59.925 --> 00:11:01.527
the continued existence
of those camps

00:11:01.627 --> 00:11:03.962
brings us to a really important
point to understand.

00:11:04.062 --> 00:11:07.232
Kim Jong-un is terrified
of losing power.

00:11:07.332 --> 00:11:10.236
And while we love to present him
as a madman, many experts

00:11:10.336 --> 00:11:12.404
believe that his actions are
motivated by rational

00:11:12.504 --> 00:11:13.505
self-preservation.

00:11:13.906 --> 00:11:17.075
He has seen leaders like Saddam
Hussein and Muammar Gadhafi

00:11:17.275 --> 00:11:20.378
scale back their nuclear
programs, only to be overthrown,

00:11:20.479 --> 00:11:22.882
either by the U.S.,
or by their own people,

00:11:22.982 --> 00:11:24.183
and die gruesome deaths.

00:11:24.383 --> 00:11:26.485
And it's true that dictators
generally don't

00:11:26.585 --> 00:11:29.588
end their careers like disgraced
American politicians,

00:11:29.688 --> 00:11:31.724
with a stint on
<i> Dancing with the Stars,</i>

00:11:31.824 --> 00:11:34.993
although, that would've been
an incredible season.

00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:39.064
Saddam, that foxtrot
was a weapon of mass seduction.

00:11:39.164 --> 00:11:41.766
And, Muammar...
You worked hard and it showed.

00:11:41.866 --> 00:11:43.135
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:11:43.235 --> 00:11:47.539
So, Kim Jong-un has continued
his family's military-first

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:52.211
policy, spending huge amounts
of money on what is the fourth
largest military on Earth

00:11:52.311 --> 00:11:54.213
and an expensive
nuclear program

00:11:54.313 --> 00:11:57.115
in an impoverished country whose
economy has been estimated

00:11:57.215 --> 00:12:00.018
to be smaller than that
of Birmingham, Alabama.

00:12:00.485 --> 00:12:02.621
And Birmingham is
a small economy.

00:12:02.721 --> 00:12:04.256
Their most notable export

00:12:04.356 --> 00:12:06.958
is<i> American Idol</i> season five
winner, Taylor Hicks.

00:12:07.058 --> 00:12:09.494
Not that I'm saying that's
a bad thing.

00:12:09.594 --> 00:12:10.696
Soul patrol forever!

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:13.232
Soul patrol 'till I fucking die!

00:12:13.799 --> 00:12:18.370
So, how can Kim Jong-un
justify that spending?

00:12:18.470 --> 00:12:21.406
Well, he argues that the huge
military is the only thing

00:12:21.506 --> 00:12:24.209
staving off imminent invasion
from a host of outsiders

00:12:24.309 --> 00:12:26.545
and that is where we come in.

00:12:26.879 --> 00:12:29.281
Because the most dominant
and useful villain

00:12:29.381 --> 00:12:31.383
in North Korea's narrative
is the United States.

00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:33.919
And it is not like that comes
out of nowhere.

00:12:34.019 --> 00:12:36.321
We sided with the south
during the Korean War.

00:12:36.421 --> 00:12:38.457
And while many Americans
may have forgotten just

00:12:38.557 --> 00:12:39.792
how devastating that war was,

00:12:39.892 --> 00:12:42.060
the North Koreans
certainly haven't.

00:12:42.160 --> 00:12:44.396
They have
an entire museum devoted

00:12:44.496 --> 00:12:45.664
to American war atrocities.

00:12:46.198 --> 00:12:50.068
And I'm not saying there were
none, but I don't think any were

00:12:50.168 --> 00:12:51.871
quite as over-the-top as this.

00:12:52.738 --> 00:12:53.639
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

00:12:54.106 --> 00:12:56.375 line:0%
REPORTER:<i> In the last liberation
 war, during our strategic</i>

00:12:56.475 --> 00:13:00.746
<i> retreat, the American hyenas
 occupied the land of Sinchon.</i>

00:13:00.846 --> 00:13:02.648
<i> They arrested Min Youngshik</i>

00:13:03.015 --> 00:13:05.450
<i> and stabbed her muscles with a
 three-pronged spear</i>

00:13:05.551 --> 00:13:07.018
<i> and sucked her flowing blood.</i>

00:13:07.452 --> 00:13:10.289
<i> They also took the flesh from
 her thighs using a bayonet,</i>

00:13:10.489 --> 00:13:12.324
<i> dipped it in salt, and ate it.</i>

00:13:13.025 --> 00:13:15.427
And, in case you were
wondering, yes, you can buy

00:13:15.527 --> 00:13:17.563
coasters depicting that scene
in the museum gift shop,

00:13:17.663 --> 00:13:18.897
but they are 16 dollars,

00:13:18.997 --> 00:13:20.866
which is the real
war crime there!

00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:24.269
And the North Koreans'
indoctrination

00:13:24.369 --> 00:13:26.938
in anti-Americanism starts
extremely young,

00:13:27.038 --> 00:13:28.340
as one defector remembers.

00:13:43.188 --> 00:13:44.690
-Holy shit!
-(AUDIENCE GASPS)

00:13:44.790 --> 00:13:47.292
It is fascinating when
a country's culture seeps

00:13:47.392 --> 00:13:48.961
even into their math lessons,

00:13:49.061 --> 00:13:50.095
although,
it's not really surprising.

00:13:50.195 --> 00:13:52.197
As a British child,
our math questions were,

00:13:52.297 --> 00:13:55.668
"If Johnny has two artifacts
and Dinesh has two artifacts,

00:13:55.901 --> 00:13:58.504
then how many artifacts
is Johnny about to have?

00:13:58.604 --> 00:14:02.307
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)
-The answer, of course,
"All the artifacts."

00:14:02.741 --> 00:14:05.411
Dinesh's family can come visit
them in the British museum

00:14:05.844 --> 00:14:07.245
whenever they're in town.

00:14:08.079 --> 00:14:11.517
And the notion that North Korea
is working on a bomb that can,

00:14:11.617 --> 00:14:13.352
"Kill all the
American bastards,"

00:14:13.452 --> 00:14:15.420
is a tremendous source
of national pride,

00:14:15.687 --> 00:14:18.890
there have been stamps depicting
missiles hurtling towards

00:14:18.990 --> 00:14:20.792
the U.S. Capitol,
and a few years ago,

00:14:20.892 --> 00:14:23.495
they produced a video depicting
the destruction of New York,

00:14:23.762 --> 00:14:26.464
set to the least appropriate
song imaginable.

00:14:26.831 --> 00:14:29.001
(♪ WE ARE THE WORLD ♪
INSTRUMENTAL PLAYING)

00:14:41.246 --> 00:14:42.715
Yes, you heard right.

00:14:42.815 --> 00:14:45.483
That was a karaoke version
of<i> "We are the World",</i>

00:14:45.583 --> 00:14:47.419
set to New York in flames.

00:14:47.953 --> 00:14:49.822
And the last time I saw
a karaoke song

00:14:49.922 --> 00:14:52.291
with background imagery
that inappropriate was

00:14:52.524 --> 00:14:54.959
every time I have ever
sung karaoke.

00:14:55.059 --> 00:14:55.861
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:14:56.428 --> 00:14:58.396
I don't know what L.L. Cool J's
<i> "Doin' it"</i> has to do with

00:14:58.496 --> 00:15:00.298
these two babies in a field of
sunflowers,

00:15:00.398 --> 00:15:02.734
but it's making everybody
uncomfortable.

00:15:02.834 --> 00:15:03.835
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:15:04.369 --> 00:15:07.272
So, the North Korean regime has
been very careful about

00:15:07.372 --> 00:15:10.608
presenting a threatening image
of Americans to its people.

00:15:10.708 --> 00:15:13.745
And some activists have actually
been trying to undermine that

00:15:14.012 --> 00:15:16.982
by sneaking information into the
country on USB drives.

00:15:17.682 --> 00:15:19.084 line:0%
(SPEAKING IN KOREAN)

00:15:19.284 --> 00:15:20.786 line:0%
INTERPRETER:<i> We send
 various content</i>

00:15:20.886 --> 00:15:23.255 line:0%
<i> from stories on human rights,
 general information on</i>

00:15:23.355 --> 00:15:26.391 line:0%
<i>South Korea, to images depicting
 the average American.</i>

00:15:26.791 --> 00:15:29.194 line:0%
KARLA MURTHY:
For<i> a fictional version
 of the average American,</i>

00:15:29.294 --> 00:15:32.264 line:0%
<i> TV shows like</i> The Mentalist,
<i> and</i> Desperate Housewives,

00:15:32.364 --> 00:15:35.133 line:0%
<i> Kang says, scenes like
 this one from</i> NCIS...

00:15:35.467 --> 00:15:38.503 line:0%
Anything you say can and will
be used against you
in a court of law.

00:15:38.603 --> 00:15:40.472 line:0%
MURTHY:<i> ...That show police
 officers reading suspects</i>

00:15:40.572 --> 00:15:42.474 line:0%
<i> their rights,
 are especially useful.</i>

00:15:42.941 --> 00:15:45.611
You know what? If nothing else,
we finally have our answer

00:15:45.711 --> 00:15:47.046
to the decade-long question,

00:15:47.146 --> 00:15:49.681
"Who the fuck
is watching<i> NCIS?"</i>

00:15:49.781 --> 00:15:50.715
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:15:50.815 --> 00:15:53.018
It turns out,
it's all your mom's friends

00:15:53.118 --> 00:15:54.753
and the people of North Korea.

00:15:55.487 --> 00:15:58.056
And if you think about it,
that is very dangerous

00:15:58.157 --> 00:16:00.759
for Kim Jong-un,
because if people get a sense

00:16:00.959 --> 00:16:03.228
that the image of America
that he has carefully painted

00:16:03.328 --> 00:16:05.631
for them is false,
he could have huge problems.

00:16:05.864 --> 00:16:07.766
And, when you understand
him in that light,

00:16:07.866 --> 00:16:11.269
as a dictator desperately
hedging against a loss of power,

00:16:11.369 --> 00:16:14.239
it is possible to understand why
all his recent threats

00:16:14.339 --> 00:16:16.274
against the United States,
have been reckless,

00:16:16.541 --> 00:16:18.610
but in his mind, also rational.

00:16:19.077 --> 00:16:21.313
And that brings us to
the key question here,

00:16:21.413 --> 00:16:23.181
what are we going to do
about this?

00:16:23.382 --> 00:16:25.283
Because on the campaign trail,
Donald Trump

00:16:25.383 --> 00:16:26.718
made it all seem very simple.

00:16:27.218 --> 00:16:32.057 line:0%
They said, "Would you speak
to the leader of North Korea?"

00:16:32.858 --> 00:16:36.128 line:0%
I said, "Absolutely. Why not?
Why not?"

00:16:36.628 --> 00:16:39.765 line:0%
And they come out, "Trump would
speak to him!"

00:16:40.899 --> 00:16:43.568 line:0%
Who the hell cares?
I'll speak to anybody.

00:16:44.136 --> 00:16:46.237 line:0%
-(AUDIENCE CHEERING FOR TRUMP)
-Who knows?

00:16:46.471 --> 00:16:49.307 line:0%
There's a ten percent
or a 20 percent chance

00:16:50.075 --> 00:16:52.510 line:0%
that I can talk him out
of those damn nukes,

00:16:52.611 --> 00:16:54.780 line:0%
'cause who the hell wants him
to have nukes?

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:56.414 line:0%
And there's a chance!

00:16:56.881 --> 00:17:00.085
-No! No! There really isn't.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

00:17:00.185 --> 00:17:02.654
Partly because, remember,
Kim Jong-un believes they are

00:17:02.754 --> 00:17:04.790
critical for his survival,
and on top of that,

00:17:04.890 --> 00:17:07.492
Donald Trump is a shitty
negotiator.

00:17:07.859 --> 00:17:10.162
In his short presidency,
he has failed to get Mexico

00:17:10.262 --> 00:17:12.364
to pay for his stupid wall,
he's failed to get

00:17:12.464 --> 00:17:15.700
a Congress his party controls
to pass a health care bill,

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:18.336
and even when his administration
does get something done,

00:17:18.437 --> 00:17:21.072
it way oversells it,
like when the White House

00:17:21.172 --> 00:17:23.174
announced a trade deal with
China as,

00:17:23.274 --> 00:17:26.912
"Very Big News," "Gigantic," and
"Herculean,"

00:17:27.012 --> 00:17:29.347
and one much-celebrated
component turned out to be

00:17:29.447 --> 00:17:32.751
lifting a ban on beef imports
that China had preliminarily

00:17:32.851 --> 00:17:34.553
agreed to last September.

00:17:34.653 --> 00:17:36.921
So way to fucking go there,
Donald!

00:17:37.021 --> 00:17:39.191
What a very big, herculean deal!

00:17:39.291 --> 00:17:42.628
Thanks to you, except,
not entirely thanks to you,

00:17:42.728 --> 00:17:46.631
America is now marginally
more able to export beef again!

00:17:46.731 --> 00:17:47.666
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

00:17:47.766 --> 00:17:49.267
And since taking office,

00:17:49.367 --> 00:17:51.903
Trump has voiced support
for an even simpler solution.

00:17:52.437 --> 00:17:55.207 line:0%
China... is helping us

00:17:56.475 --> 00:17:58.610 line:0%
possibly or probably,

00:17:58.811 --> 00:18:02.847 line:0%
with the North Korean situation.

00:18:03.615 --> 00:18:05.617 line:0%
-(AUDIENCE CHEERS)
-Okay? Which is a great thing.

00:18:05.917 --> 00:18:06.718
Great thing.

00:18:07.352 --> 00:18:09.420
So, in the space of 14
seconds there,

00:18:09.521 --> 00:18:11.189
he said the word "great" twice,

00:18:11.423 --> 00:18:14.058
he pronounced "China"
with three syllables,

00:18:14.292 --> 00:18:16.361
suggested someone else should
do the work for him,

00:18:16.462 --> 00:18:18.463
and then, threw in a
"possibly or probably,"

00:18:18.563 --> 00:18:19.932
rendering the whole
thing meaningless.

00:18:20.032 --> 00:18:22.234
I think I may have just hit
Trump bingo,

00:18:22.334 --> 00:18:24.869
and the prize that I want
is to go drown in a river.

00:18:24.969 --> 00:18:25.904
(CROWD LAUGHS)

00:18:26.004 --> 00:18:29.708
But Trump's idea there
of convincing China

00:18:29.808 --> 00:18:31.743
to exert influence
on North Korea,

00:18:31.843 --> 00:18:33.545
is not inherently crazy.

00:18:33.745 --> 00:18:36.414
China shares an 800-mile border
with North Korea

00:18:36.514 --> 00:18:38.283
and accounts for
as much as 90 percent

00:18:38.383 --> 00:18:39.717
of North Korea's total trade,

00:18:39.817 --> 00:18:41.419
so they do have
significant leverage.

00:18:41.519 --> 00:18:45.056
But, some are skeptical about
just what China could,

00:18:45.156 --> 00:18:46.558
or is willing to do.

00:18:46.658 --> 00:18:49.761
Take sanctions. The U.N.
have tried multiple rounds

00:18:49.861 --> 00:18:52.965
of increasingly-harsh sanctions,
but North Korea has always found

00:18:53.065 --> 00:18:54.166
easy ways around them.

00:18:54.666 --> 00:18:56.034
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

00:18:56.134 --> 00:18:58.736 line:0%
INTERPRETER:<i> North Korea is a
 100% state enterprise,</i>

00:18:59.003 --> 00:19:01.205 line:0%
<i> so these companies change
 their names the next day</i>

00:19:01.306 --> 00:19:02.640 line:0%
<i>if they're listed for sanctions.</i>

00:19:03.041 --> 00:19:05.710 line:0%
<i> That way the company stays,
 but with different names</i>

00:19:05.811 --> 00:19:07.312
<i> whenever there are sanctions.</i>

00:19:07.412 --> 00:19:10.649
<i> If I'm included in the list,
 my name can be changed, too.</i>

